{"parse":{"title":"Mary Rippon","pageid":57418307,"revid":855336995,"text":{"*":"<div class=\"mw-parser-output\"><table class=\"infobox biography vcard\" style=\"width:22em\"><tbody><tr><th colspan=\"2\" style=\"text-align:center;font-size:125%;font-weight:bold\"><span class=\"fn\">Mary Rippon</span></th></tr><tr><th scope=\"row\">Born</th><td>\n<span style=\"display:none\">(<span class=\"bday\">1850-05-25</span>)</span>May 25, 1850<br /><span class=\"birthplace\"><a href=\"/wiki/Lisbon,_Illinois\" title=\"Lisbon, Illinois\">Lisbon, Illinois</a></span></td></tr><tr><th scope=\"row\">Died</th><td>\nSeptember 8, 1935<span style=\"display:none\">(1935-09-08)</span> (aged&#160;85)<br /><span class=\"deathplace\"><a href=\"/wiki/Boulder,_Colorado\" title=\"Boulder, Colorado\">Boulder, Colorado</a></span></td></tr><tr><th scope=\"row\">Known&#160;for</th><td>\nFirst female instructor at a state university</td></tr><tr><th scope=\"row\">Children</th><td>\nMiriam Housel</td></tr></tbody></table>\n<p><br />\n<b>Mary Rippon</b> was the first woman to teach at a state university, as well as the first female professor at the <a href=\"/wiki/University_of_Colorado_Boulder\" title=\"University of Colorado Boulder\">University of Colorado Boulder</a>.<sup id=\"cite_ref-:0_1-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-:0-1\">&#91;1&#93;</a></sup> Rippon began teaching French and German at CU in 1878, became head of Germanic languages and literature, and served at the University until 1909.<sup id=\"cite_ref-:2_2-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-:2-2\">&#91;2&#93;</a></sup>  <a href=\"/wiki/University_of_Colorado_Boulder#Mary_Rippon_Theatre\" title=\"University of Colorado Boulder\">Mary Rippon Outdoor Theatre</a>, the location of the annual <a href=\"/wiki/Colorado_Shakespeare_Festival\" title=\"Colorado Shakespeare Festival\">Colorado Shakespeare Festival</a>, is named in her honor.<sup id=\"cite_ref-:4_3-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-:4-3\">&#91;3&#93;</a></sup>\n</p>\n<div id=\"toc\" class=\"toc\"><input type=\"checkbox\" role=\"button\" id=\"toctogglecheckbox\" class=\"toctogglecheckbox\" style=\"display:none\" /><div class=\"toctitle\" lang=\"en\" dir=\"ltr\"><h2>Contents</h2><span class=\"toctogglespan\"><label class=\"toctogglelabel\" for=\"toctogglecheckbox\"></label></span></div>\n<ul>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-1\"><a href=\"#Early_Life\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">1</span> <span class=\"toctext\">Early Life</span></a></li>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-2\"><a href=\"#Education_and_Career\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">2</span> <span class=\"toctext\">Education and Career</span></a></li>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-3\"><a href=\"#Personal_Life\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">3</span> <span class=\"toctext\">Personal Life</span></a></li>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-4\"><a href=\"#Posthumous_Honors\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">4</span> <span class=\"toctext\">Posthumous Honors</span></a></li>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-5\"><a href=\"#References\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">5</span> <span class=\"toctext\">References</span></a></li>\n</ul>\n</div>\n\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"Early_Life\">Early Life</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Mary_Rippon&amp;action=edit&amp;section=1\" title=\"Edit section: Early Life\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<p>Mary Rippon was born May 25, 1850 in <a href=\"/wiki/Lisbon,_Illinois\" title=\"Lisbon, Illinois\">Lisbon, Illinois</a> to Thomas Rippon and Jane Skinner, who had immigrated from England.<sup id=\"cite_ref-:1_4-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-:1-4\">&#91;4&#93;</a></sup><sup id=\"cite_ref-Burial_5-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-Burial-5\">&#91;5&#93;</a></sup> Her father died when she was ten months old, and because he did not leave a will and Mary was his only child, she inherited his farm. After her mother abandoned her, she lived with neighbors and extended family.<sup id=\"cite_ref-:2_2-1\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-:2-2\">&#91;2&#93;</a></sup>\n</p><p>She attended the high school department of <a href=\"/wiki/Illinois_State_Normal_University\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Illinois State Normal University\">Illinois State Normal University</a>, a teacher training school.<sup id=\"cite_ref-:3_6-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-:3-6\">&#91;6&#93;</a></sup> Money from the sale of the farm funded her education,<sup id=\"cite_ref-7\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-7\">&#91;7&#93;</a></sup> and when she turned 18 she had access to the remainder of her inheritance.<sup id=\"cite_ref-8\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-8\">&#91;8&#93;</a></sup>\n</p><p>After high school, Rippon spent five years studying in Germany, Switzerland, and France.<sup id=\"cite_ref-:3_6-1\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-:3-6\">&#91;6&#93;</a></sup>\n</p>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"Education_and_Career\">Education and Career</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Mary_Rippon&amp;action=edit&amp;section=2\" title=\"Edit section: Education and Career\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<p>Rippon taught German at a high school in Detroit for one school year from 1876 to 1877. In 1877, she received an offer of employment from Joseph Sewall, who had taught at Illinois Normal School and was the first president of the newly established University of Colorado.<sup id=\"cite_ref-:3_6-2\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-:3-6\">&#91;6&#93;</a></sup> She joined the <a href=\"/wiki/University_of_Colorado_Boulder\" title=\"University of Colorado Boulder\">University of Colorado</a> faculty in January 1878.<sup id=\"cite_ref-9\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-9\">&#91;9&#93;</a></sup> Rippon arrived at the University of Colorado to teach German and French language and literature; during the first term she also taught English grammar and mathematics.<sup id=\"cite_ref-:3_6-3\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-:3-6\">&#91;6&#93;</a></sup> In 1891 she became head of the Department of Modern Languages, which later became the Department of Germanic Languages and Literature.<sup id=\"cite_ref-:2_2-2\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-:2-2\">&#91;2&#93;</a></sup> Mary Rippon retired from teaching in 1909.<sup id=\"cite_ref-:0_1-1\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-:0-1\">&#91;1&#93;</a></sup>\n</p>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"Personal_Life\">Personal Life</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Mary_Rippon&amp;action=edit&amp;section=3\" title=\"Edit section: Personal Life\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<p>In 1887, at age thirty-seven Rippon met Will Housel, a student in her German class, who was then twenty-five. The two engaged in a romantic relationship. When she became pregnant, Rippon took a year off from teaching and went to Europe, secretly marrying Housel in St. Louis on the way. When she returned to the university, her daughter Miriam remained behind, first with Housel and later in an orphanage. Housel returned to Colorado, but the two never lived together. Rippon provided financial support to Miriam and Housel, even after he remarried. Rippon occasionally visited her daughter, but Miriam believed Rippon was her aunt.<sup id=\"cite_ref-:3_6-4\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-:3-6\">&#91;6&#93;</a></sup>\n</p><p>Rippon\u2019s family remained a secret, even while Miriam taught at the <a href=\"/wiki/University_of_Colorado_Boulder\" title=\"University of Colorado Boulder\">University of Colorado</a>. In the 1970s, Miriam\u2019s son revealed that he was Rippon\u2019s descendant.<sup id=\"cite_ref-10\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-10\">&#91;10&#93;</a></sup>\n</p>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"Posthumous_Honors\">Posthumous Honors</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Mary_Rippon&amp;action=edit&amp;section=4\" title=\"Edit section: Posthumous Honors\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<p>Mary Rippon died on September 8, 1935 from <a href=\"/wiki/Myocarditis\" title=\"Myocarditis\">myocarditis</a>.<sup id=\"cite_ref-Burial_5-1\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-Burial-5\">&#91;5&#93;</a></sup> The Regents of the University of Colorado approved plans for an outdoor theatre named in her honor.<sup id=\"cite_ref-:1_4-1\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-:1-4\">&#91;4&#93;</a></sup> The Mary Rippon Theatre, located on CU's campus, hosts the annual <a href=\"/wiki/Colorado_Shakespeare_Festival\" title=\"Colorado Shakespeare Festival\">Colorado Shakespeare Festival</a> each summer.<sup id=\"cite_ref-:4_3-1\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-:4-3\">&#91;3&#93;</a></sup>\n</p><p>Rippon was awarded posthumous honorary doctorate from the <a href=\"/wiki/University_of_Colorado_Boulder\" title=\"University of Colorado Boulder\">University of Colorado</a> in May 2006.<sup id=\"cite_ref-:2_2-3\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-:2-2\">&#91;2&#93;</a></sup><sup id=\"cite_ref-11\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-11\">&#91;11&#93;</a></sup>\n</p>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"References\">References</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Mary_Rippon&amp;action=edit&amp;section=5\" title=\"Edit section: References\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<div class=\"mw-references-wrap mw-references-columns\"><ol class=\"references\">\n<li id=\"cite_note-:0-1\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\">^ <a href=\"#cite_ref-:0_1-0\"><sup><i><b>a</b></i></sup></a> <a href=\"#cite_ref-:0_1-1\"><sup><i><b>b</b></i></sup></a></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><cite class=\"citation news\"><a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"https://www.colorado.edu/libraries/2018/03/03/mary-rippon-first-cu-female-professor\">\"Mary Rippon, the first CU female professor\"</a>. <i>University Libraries</i>. 2018-03-03<span class=\"reference-accessdate\">. Retrieved <span class=\"nowrap\">2018-05-14</span></span>.</cite><span title=\"ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Ajournal&amp;rft.genre=article&amp;rft.jtitle=University+Libraries&amp;rft.atitle=Mary+Rippon%2C+the+first+CU+female+professor&amp;rft.date=2018-03-03&amp;rft_id=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.colorado.edu%2Flibraries%2F2018%2F03%2F03%2Fmary-rippon-first-cu-female-professor&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3AMary+Rippon\" class=\"Z3988\"><span style=\"display:none;\">&#160;</span></span></span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-:2-2\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\">^ <a href=\"#cite_ref-:2_2-0\"><sup><i><b>a</b></i></sup></a> <a href=\"#cite_ref-:2_2-1\"><sup><i><b>b</b></i></sup></a> <a href=\"#cite_ref-:2_2-2\"><sup><i><b>c</b></i></sup></a> <a href=\"#cite_ref-:2_2-3\"><sup><i><b>d</b></i></sup></a></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><cite class=\"citation news\"><a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"http://www.dailycamera.com/ci_13058123\">\"Pettem: Mary Rippon to receive posthumous honorary degree\"</a><span class=\"reference-accessdate\">. Retrieved <span class=\"nowrap\">2018-06-22</span></span>.</cite><span title=\"ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Ajournal&amp;rft.genre=article&amp;rft.atitle=Pettem%3A+Mary+Rippon+to+receive+posthumous+honorary+degree&amp;rft_id=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.dailycamera.com%2Fci_13058123&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3AMary+Rippon\" class=\"Z3988\"><span style=\"display:none;\">&#160;</span></span></span>\n</li>\n<li i